              </section>
            </aside>

            <section class="stage" aria-label="Inline Artemis II price diagram">
              <div class="rocket-shell">
                <div class="rocket-window">
                  <article class="rocket-slide" aria-label={artemisSlide?.label}>
                    <span class="rocket-label">{artemisSlide?.label}</span>
                    <div set:html={artemisSlide?.svg ?? ''} />
                  </article>
                </div>
              </div>
            </section>

            <div class="tooltip" data-tooltip aria-hidden="true">
              <strong data-tooltip-part></strong>
              <span data-tooltip-contractor></span>
              <span data-tooltip-price></span>
              <span data-tooltip-description></span>
            </div>
          </section>

          <p class="article-copy">As said, Artemis is an unprecedented mission in terms of its scope and scale. Of course, this means it couldn’t have been done alone. For Artemis, NASA turned to its reliable team of private contractors. NASA’s team is a highly specialized network that the organization has been in collaboration with since lunar spaceflight was first conceptualized in the 1960s. Let’s take a closer look at the companies that made the Artemis II launch happen:</p>

          <section class="inline-diagram inline-diagram--parts diagram-panel" data-diagram-panel data-initial-mode="contractors" data-inline-price-simple="true" aria-label="Diagram 2: Artemis II parts diagram">
